  "prompt": "How can I add a floating chart (like freezing top row) in Excel 2013?",
  "response": "To add a floating (or frozen) top row in Excel 2013, follow these steps:\n\n1. Open your Excel spreadsheet\n\n2. Go to the \"View\" tab in the ribbon\n\n3. In the \"Window\" section, click on \"Freeze Panes\"\n\n4. You have three options:\n   - Freeze Panes: Freezes rows and columns at the current selection\n   - Freeze Top Row: Locks the top row in place\n   - Freeze First Column: Locks the first column in place\n\n5. To freeze specific rows/columns:\n   - Select the cell below the rows you want to freeze\n   - Click \"Freeze Panes\" under the \"View\" tab\n\n6. To unfreeze:\n   - Go to \"View\" tab\n   - Click \"Freeze Panes\"\n   - Select \"Unfreeze Panes\"\n\nTips:\n- Best for headers or reference rows\n- Helps keep important information visible while scrolling\n- Works well with large datasets\n\nPro tip: You can also use the keyboard shortcut Alt + W + F to quickly access Freeze Panes.",
